    • Method Detail

      • onApprove

        public void onApprove(java.util.HashMap<java.lang.String,java.lang.String> returnParams)
        onApprove() method will be called if the transaction is finished processing from the SDK.

        This function will receive return params containing information related to the transaction from the checkout experience.

        Sample values for returnParams : { PayerID=payerId, return_uri=https://sample.com/finished?someparam=somevalue, paymentId=PAYID-transactionID, opType=payment, token=transactionToken }

        For integrating apps rendering their webPage in a WebView, the default behavior is to redirect the integrating app's webView to the appropriate url returned. But the integrating apps can always override this behavior.

        If the integrating apps is a Native app, they are required to override this method in order to do post checkout functionality. More information about finishing a transaction can be found in the developer portal.

        Parameters:
        returnParams - - includes params passed back from the checkout that are required by the integrating app to finish transaction.

      • checkoutFailed

        public void checkoutFailed()
        checkoutFailed() method will be called if the SDK is unable to finish the transaction in the native paySheet.

        Sample scenarios when this method will be called, An exception occurred in some part of the SDK. The user could not be authenticated natively. SDK was unable to fetch the payload required to surface the native paysheet.

        The Default behavior of the application is to fall back to a ^Custom Tab.

        integrating apps are not recommended to override this method, as this method ensures that the user can complete the transaction in case of failures.

        NOTE: ^Custom Tab is a hybrid between a WebView and a Browser that gives a secure implementation while showing a more seamless experience. More information about Chrome's version of Custom tabs can be found here

      • checkoutContingency

        public void checkoutContingency(java.lang.String url)
        checkoutContingency() method will be called if a contingency is raised while the user is interacting with the paysheet.

        A contingency is a scenario which is not currently handled by the native paysheet.

        Sample scenarios when this method will be called, User wants to add a new card.

        The Default behavior of the application is to fall back to a ^Custom Tab.

        integrating apps are not recommended to override this method, as this method ensures that the user can complete the transaction in case of failures.

        NOTE: ^Custom Tab is a hybrid between a WebView and a Browser that gives a secure implementation while showing a more seamless experience. More information about Chrome's version of Custom tabs can be found here

      • onCancel

        public void onCancel()
        onCancel() method will be called if the USER deliberately cancels the checkout flow.

        Default behavior is a to return to integrating app's webView with the cancel url that is provided on the integrating apps's application page. More information about cancel url can be found in the developer portal.

        integrating apps with native applications are required to override this to add their own behavior.

        integrating apps with hosting their app in a webView and have integrated with ^Checkout.js should not override this method.

        NOTE: ^ To know more about Checkout.js please refer to the documentation here
